	<tr>
		<td width="150" align="left" valign="top" class="row2"><span class="name"><a name="109232"></a><b>Xianin</b></span><br /><span class="postdetails">leaching off society<br />
		<br /><img src="http://webpages.charter.net/babbles/images/01b.gif" alt="Avatar" class="avatar" border="0" />
		<br />Joined: 22 Jul 2003<br />Posts: 2741</span></td>
		<td class="row2" width="100%" height="28" valign="top">

		<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
			<tr>
			<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=109232&amp;sid=b966fc1252ae3b0666d9517a374cda4f#109232"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Thu Mar 10, 2005 5:29 am<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: My disagreement with the Libertarian Party.</span></td>
				<td width="30%" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap" align="right"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=109232&amp;sid=b966fc1252ae3b0666d9517a374cda4f"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>     </td></tr></table></td>
			</tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Inspired by Poppa's pole I thought I would list out what I do not agree with in terms of the LP.  I was wondering why I scored low at that quiz thing, not that it was scientific or accurate but it was way different than I expected.
<br />
These platforms issues I disagree with can be found <a href="http://www.lp.org/issues/platform/execsumm.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">HERE</a>
<br />

<br />
As I am writing this, I realize there is a heck of a lot of things I disagree with and then there are some stances that the LP takes which I think makes them 100% nuts.  This may be a bit long.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Victimless Crimes
<br />
Only actions that infringe on the rights of others can properly be termed crimes.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Breaking the law is breaking the law regardless if other people's rights are infringed.  Drinking and driving should be illegal regardless if somebody is a victim.  I am not willing to risk the chance.  Money laundering, welfare abuse, tax evasion, piracy, and other things should still be illegal.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">The War on Drugs
<br />
The War on Drugs is a grave threat to individual liberty, to domestic order, and to peace in the world.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I am begining to become more pro-marijuana as I get older.  If it becomes legal, then that is cool.  If it doesn't, then that's cool.  However there are some really bad things out there than can really mess up parts of society.  I fail to see how allowing drugs will bring peace to the world.  Apparantly drugs are common in Afghanistan, but I hardly consider them being at peace.
<br />
This sounds like straight up hippy talk.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Government and Mental Health
<br />
We oppose the involuntary treatment for mental health by health officials or law enforcement.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
As long as it is practiced resonably so, I do not have a problem with this chiefly so when it involves the welfare of children.  Like it or not, the fact is there are some people who are medically crazy that have kids.  To protect the kids, I think involunatary treatment is acceptable.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Government Secrecy
<br />
We condemn the government's use of secret classifications to keep from the public information that it should have.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
This is just plain straight up nuts.  The last thing we need is Syria surfing the net and getting blueprints to our Navy vessels or finding out information about our military aircraft.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">The Right to Keep and Bear Arms
<br />
We affirm the right to keep and bear arms and oppose all laws at any level of government restricting, regulating, or requiring the ownership, manufacture, transfer, or sale of firearms or ammunition.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I do think that there should be a cursory background check and require a license for conceal and carry.  Even down here in pro-gun Texas people accept the requirement to go to classes before they are allowed to concel and carry.  We also should not allow the sale of straight up military type weapons.  I am not talking about M-16 type guns, but like machine guns, .50 caliber guns, and things of that nature.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Immigration
<br />
We hold that human rights should not be denied or abridged on the basis of nationality and welcome all refugees to our country.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
As long as they do so within the confines of our laws; legal immigration is cool.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Families and Children
<br />
We believe that families are private institutions, which should be free from government intrusion, and that parents have the right to raise their children according to their own standards and beliefs.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Unless those standards and beliefs involve sacraficing the first born.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">American Indian Rights
<br />
American Indians should be free to determine their own system of governance and should have their property rights restored.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I am of the mind to tell those Native Americans to get over it.  This is the 21st century.  Either become American citizens like the rest of us, or move to Canada.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">The Economy
<br />
Government intervention in the economy imperils both the personal freedom and the material prosperity of every American.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
The government is part of the economy.  Always has and always will.  The moment the government decides to collect taxes or purchase items (such as military items which is basically outlined in the Constitution therefore within their rights) there will be an impact.  I think the US government has proven that they can have a reasonable intervention and still allow a free market.  Proof being that we have arguably the best market in the world.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Taxation
<br />
All persons are entitled to keep the fruits of their labor. We oppose all government activity that consists of the forcible collection of money or goods from individuals in violation of their individual rights.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I don't enjoy paying taxes.  I don't enjoy going to the dentist either.  However those things need to be done.  The federal government has a Constitutional responsibility to see to the protection of the country, as well as other duties.  They are, therefore, required to get funding to carry out those duties.  
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Finance and Capital Investment
<br />
Regulation of financial and capital markets represses capital ventures.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Again, the government is involved with the market place.  Having the government set standards for accounting and good management principles is a good thing.  Over regulation, of course, is bad but there does need to be some basic rules and regulations.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Government Debt
<br />
We support a constitutional amendment requiring government budgets be balanced by cutting expenditures and not by raising taxes.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
While a balanced budget sounds good, it is not always possible.  Some years you are going to have to run a defecit, and some years you will be in the black.  Marketplace and world economic factors don't follow a fiscal year; things happen over the course of several years so it is silly to expect our government to respond by forcing our budget into an 'unnatural' budget.  Let it reflect the economy.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Subsidies
<br />
The unrestricted competition of the free market is the best way to foster prosperity. We oppose all government subsidies.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
In no way do I want to encourage more subsidies, however to a certain degree in some industries there are a real need of subsidies.  For instance take a look at the human genome project.  Much of it was subsidized by the NIH and other gvt agencies.  NASA was a nice little government subsidies.  I am convinced that we learned way more due to this 'crazy' subsidy than anything we lost.  I would rather see our tax money used to subsidize certain things in various industries instead of seeing other countries subsidize those very same industries in their country.  In some instances, such as the human genome project, the scientific knowledge of our country would fall far behind that of other countries.  Many of you people argue for fuel cell powered vehicles, and if that is ever going to work it will require government subsidies.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Pollution
<br />
Pollution of other people's property is a violation of individual rights. Strict liability, not government agencies and arbitrary government standards, should regulate pollution.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Being that I used to work in the environmental testing field, I will atest to the fact that the government standards are not arbitrary.  The LP then obviously does not understand this issue.  If they do not understand this issue, then how can they develop a policy concerning this?
<br />
I think we need a government agency to act as a third party.  Else we will get a bunch of he said/she said stuff going on as companies or citizens accuse each other of pollution.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Education
<br />
We advocate the complete separation of education and State.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I am all for encouraging private schools, but I think it is crazy to totally eliminate government involvement in education.  Universities, by the way, are another thing I think that should be subsidized by the federal government.  As cliche as it sounds, eductation is indeed a major determining factor in the success of a society.  I therefore feel that providing education to the citizens is one of the best things government can do.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Health Care
<br />
We favor restoring and reviving a free market health care system. We advocate a complete separation of medicine and State.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Complete?  As in remove the FDA?  I think this is yet another misinformed and, for lack of a better term, stupid idea on part of the LP.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Occupational Safety and Health Act (OSHA)
<br />
We call for the repeal of OSHA, which denies the right to liberty and property to both employer and employee and interferes in private contractual relations.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Have these people ever have a job?  Working in the chemistry field I am hella happy for OSHA.  OSHA has, without a doubt in my mind, saved many many lifes.  I fail to see how OSHA regulations are something that we need to eliminate.  Again, working in the chemistry field, i.e. hazardous materials, I am thankful as hell for OSHA.  It is nice to know that companies are required to send a Material Safety Data Sheet (MSDS) with their product so I know what the hell it is!
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Civil Service
<br />
The Civil Service system entrenches a permanent and growing bureaucracy and is inherently a system of concealed patronage.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
WTF?  These people do not think things through!  Any possible job involving the government is civil service.  I am not saying that there is no corruption or issues or that there is no room for improvement, but to imply that the entire system is bad and needs to be scrapped is just crazy.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Negotiations
<br />
The important principle in foreign policy should be the elimination of intervention by the United States government in the affairs of other nations.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Sure, this sounds all nice and peachy, but you know what one of the specific roles in the US Constitution states that the federal government will see to the safety of the US and specifically addresses treaties.  Therefore it is implied in the US Constitution, the almighty document in this country, that the federal governemnt is to negotiate with foreign countries.  If such treaties require us to intervene, then so be it.  If we need to intervene for our own protection then so be it.
<br />
For a party that claims to want to return to the essence of the Constitution, they sure do seem to ignore many specific points in the Constiution.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">World Government
<br />
We oppose U.S. government participation in any world or international government. We oppose any treaty under which individual rights would be violated.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I think the UN as it is now sucks.  That being said we can not live under a rock, there are more countries than the good ole USA.  We must deal with other countries.  I do not want any national organization to violate our individual rights, but I do think the US should participate in the international scene.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Presidential War Powers
<br />
We favor limiting the presidential role as Commander-in-Chief to its original meaning, namely that of the head of the armed forces in wartime.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Man, the LP is just getting stupid.  They read the first part of Section 2 in the US Constitution but managed to fail to read the parts that specifically states that the President can make treaties, appoint officeholders, sign bills, and so forth.  I mentioned it earlier and I mention it again now; the LP seems to be very selective of what items in the Constitution they wish to follow.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Foreign Aid
<br />
We support the elimination of tax-supported military, economic, technical, and scientific aid to foreign governments or other organizations.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Again, we are not alone in the world.  I do not think we should casually just fork over money left and right, but the fact that we are a charitable nation is part of our societal fabric.  I got the feeling that the LP wants to get rid of all international contacts and be literal shut-ins.  That is not a country I wish to live in.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Foreign Intervention
<br />
We would end the current U.S. government policy of foreign intervention, including military and economic aid, guarantees, and diplomatic meddling. We make no exceptions.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
No exceptions, eh?   There is a good way to get the vote of military veterens.  Again, there are more things in the world than just our country.  Sending econimic aid to rebuilding nations is a good thing; just ask Japan and Germany.  This is just another example of the LP not thinking things through.
<br />
Haha, no exceptions . . .
<br />

<br />

<br />
I used to think I supported many of the Libertarian Party messages, but after really reading more about what they stand for I really do think they are a nutty fringe group.  Many of their platform stances "sound good" however the problem is that they really have not seemed to have thought things through.  I think the LP appeals to many of you people because they do attempt to be up front about their stances, but the problem with that is politics change, society changes, the world changes.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
