###
<br />

<br />
Xianin,
<br />

<br />
Libertarian principles are hard fast.  One thing ou can say about Libertarians is that you can count on their foundations holding strong.  They do not waver in their philosophy for expedience though they are quite pragmatic.  Libertarians do not pretend that they are the only political party or philsophy.
<br />

<br />
I was tempted to quote you and reply to each of your points but there are too many and you are nitpicking with some.  I can address your criticism in general though by forwarding a missing concept in your approach.  Those platform positions do not at all include alternative remedies.  You argue philsophy against practicality, but you do not quote any libertarian pragmatism.
<br />

<br />
Its not fair to point at a principle and say it is not practical.  By definition you are correct.  It may be more constructive to challenge not the principle but ask how would a libertarian address these problems differently?  Then discuss the practicality of alternate solutions.
<br />

<br />
There is always more than one way to skin a cat, Libertarians promote seeking new solutions to old problems that are as liberty minded as possible.  The principles are a useful guide to where lines are better drawn when considering new solutions.
<br />

<br />
I'd love to argue some of your points, but please pick one or two at a time... just to keep it practical... of course. <img src="images/smiles/smile.gif" alt="smile" border="0" /><br />
