				<div class="postbody">
				Poppa,
<br />

<br />
No, sorry.
<br />

<br />
While modern libertarianism has quite a bit in common with classical liberalism, modern libertarianism takes many of its stances much, much farther than the people you're referring to back in the 1700s did.  They take them to a point that they have more in common with anarchists than with classic liberals.  Hence why libertarians are pretty much divided between minarchists and anarcho-capitalists, with minarchists being the more moderate, and anarcho-capitalists being the more radical.
<br />

<br />
The entire problem with the libertarian party is that while some of you are, you know, rational, and understand that limiting the government too far would be disastrous, there are far more of you that can't look at long-term effects at all.  The ideas that you propose would generate mass chaos and a decline of the country in general, due to the simple fact that you're ignorant of how a country is run.
<br />

<br />
Flarestar Bladesinger<br />
