			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				I think you'll find that a number of these views are intentionally listed in the most extreme way possible so that people know, up front, what the party stands for. Everything and every view in the libertarian party stems from one simple principle, and that is that you own your body. If you find yourself in disagreement with a stance, it is a good idea if you think it through and wonder, "How does this view on this issue arise from the idea that every man is his own master?"
<br />

<br />
It is fine to list the party stances, but also unfair to list them without the proposed solutions and suggestions the LP has for alternatives to the current systems that they disagree with. Also, keep in mind reasons like, "It's never been done before" or "That's not the way things work in this country" are not justifications for continuing to use @#%$ system. No excuses.
<br />

<br />
You'll also find that a lot of the LP's current members do not see eye to eye with LP policy on several issues, despite agreeing in principle. Most libertarians are there because they are sick of misrepresentation from the big two, and the LP is the most sane of the alternatives, and the one most likely to stick to their guns and represent individual rights and liberty at the expense of all other factors. That's the party's main draw, especially on young people.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Breaking the law is breaking the law regardless if other people's rights are infringed. Drinking and driving should be illegal regardless if somebody is a victim. I am not willing to risk the chance. Money laundering, welfare abuse, tax evasion, piracy, and other things should still be illegal. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Like it or not, that is what personal responsibility means. If your actions harm another person, only then is there any crime and any reason for punishment. You'll find that most of the financial crimes you listed do in fact hurt someone, somewhere. Welfare abuse injures those paying for the welfare, piracy injures those provably deprived of profit, tax evasion hurts the government. 
<br />

<br />
Don't think of DWI as a crime... think of it as a revokation of your right to drive because you violated the contract you agreed to abide by when you obtained your driver's license. Driving is not a right; it's a priviledge. You must apply for a license, and meet set criteria to obtain it. The state can revoke your ability to do so based on any criteria it can pass in its legislature. One of those criteria currently in force is that you refrain from driving while under the influence of substances that impair your judgement and reaction time. Most people do not find this unreasonable, including most libertarians.
<br />

<br />
Plenty of people still drink and drive; don't pretend the law makes the problem go away. Friends preventing friends from doing it <span style="font-style: italic">because it is a bad idea</span> has done far more to prevent drunk driving than preventing people from doing it just because it is against the law. The law really does nothing more than revoking the license so the offender cannot drive again for a long time, and it screws him on his insurance and liability (a natural consequence of his irresponsible use of his priviledge). He chose to drive drunk, therefore he accepts responsibility for what happens.
<br />

<br />
You'll find libertarians object to police checkpoints (as a form of unreasonable search) investigating all cars on a given highway far more than they do to drunk driving laws. Be careful not to confuse the issue. I doubt any libertarian would have a problem with a police officer pulling over a car swerving all over the road and finding the driver drunk; I certainly wouldn't.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> I am begining to become more pro-marijuana as I get older. If it becomes legal, then that is cool. If it doesn't, then that's cool. However there are some really bad things out there than can really mess up parts of society. I fail to see how allowing drugs will bring peace to the world. Apparantly drugs are common in Afghanistan, but I hardly consider them being at peace. This sounds like straight up hippy talk. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Nobody is refraining from doing drugs because they are illegal. If people want to try them, no law is going to get in their way. We may as well remove the laws and bring that black market back into the regular world economy, so that criminals are deprived of one of their chief sources of income. It is a "war" that cannot be won at any price, so it is pointless to fight it. 
<br />

<br />
All historical data from prohibition and drug use prior to its illegalization, as well as numbers on drug use in countries where it is legal, points clearly and irrefutably at the fact that drugs are more of a problem now that they are illegal than they ever were when nobody cared about them except the people using them. We've had this discussion here in another thread somewhere, links to numbers are there.
<br />

<br />
Marijuana will be the first one across the legal line, and I think that's going to happen within a decade. If libertarians somehow ended up with majority power in government I doubt very much even they would legalize all drugs overnight. Once marijuana is legalized, we can study the effect and learn what to expect, and how best to handle things like medical insurance under that paradigm. There will still be plenty of penalties for it, make no mistake... they just won't be imposed by government. Your employer can still fire you for it if they choose. Try showing up to work drunk sometime if you don't believe that.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> As long as it is practiced resonably so, I do not have a problem with this chiefly so when it involves the welfare of children. Like it or not, the fact is there are some people who are medically crazy that have kids. To protect the kids, I think involunatary treatment is acceptable. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
@#%$ the kids. I mean that in the most sincere, heartfelt way possible. I refuse to believe they should garner treatment different from adults for any reason, in any situation, especially because this is so often used as an excuse to infringe on the rights of adults. Kids are just like any other group of people, and I have never seen a rational argument for treating them differently.
<br />

<br />
Involuntary treatment might be acceptable in certain extreme situations, as you say. No law can cover all possible situations, so this is always the case with any topic. Truth is stranger than fiction. I reject the idea, however, that it should be easier if there are children involved. No special treatment.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> This is just plain straight up nuts. The last thing we need is Syria surfing the net and getting blueprints to our Navy vessels or finding out information about our military aircraft. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
You'll find I agree with you here. I think, however, that they are not referring to military secrets or matters of national security. They refer to events such as JFK's assassination. Libertarians in general would require the government to be more forthcoming than they are with respect to most matters of secrecy, and I think it's a good thing. Disclosure of military blueprints, however, is going a bit too far. The public has no use for or reason to have that information.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> I do think that there should be a cursory background check and require a license for conceal and carry. Even down here in pro-gun Texas people accept the requirement to go to classes before they are allowed to concel and carry. We also should not allow the sale of straight up military type weapons. I am not talking about M-16 type guns, but like machine guns, .50 caliber guns, and things of that nature. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Owning a gun is your right under the US Government, unlike driving a car. Personally I don't have a problem with requiring gun registration, basic training, or even a short waiting period... provided, in the end, that anyone who wants to buy a gun is allowed to do so.
