<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> I am of the mind to tell those Native Americans to get over it. This is the 21st century. Either become American citizens like the rest of us, or move to Canada. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I'm not familiar enough with the situation to have an informed opinion on it. I'm inclined to agree with you, however.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> The government is part of the economy. Always has and always will. The moment the government decides to collect taxes or purchase items (such as military items which is basically outlined in the Constitution therefore within their rights) there will be an impact. I think the US government has proven that they can have a reasonable intervention and still allow a free market. Proof being that we have arguably the best market in the world. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
We hardly have reasonable intervention. It is not the job of the government to bail out failing corporations. If they fail, that is simply the way the market works. I think you're overstating the libertarian view a bit here... their take is to go as hands-off as possible. The current government is hands-on in many ways that they simply do not need to be.
<br />

<br />
Libertarians also oppose anti-trust laws. I'm not sure I like that particular stance. Fundamentally it is correct... if a monopoly exists unjustly, a free market force will appear to correct it (witness linux vs Microsoft). Thing is, with a little push from the government, they can keep the curve closer to the center and not let it swing so strongly in one direction for so long. It's good harm prevention. It might take the free market 20 years to come up with a response, and that's 20 years of abusive monopoly. Not good. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> I don't enjoy paying taxes. I don't enjoy going to the dentist either. However those things need to be done. The federal government has a Constitutional responsibility to see to the protection of the country, as well as other duties. They are, therefore, required to get funding to carry out those duties. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
There are plenty of other ways to get funding (tons of it, actually) than taxes. Personally I don't mind paying taxes, however, I do not like the current tax system, because it is corrupt and easily exploitable, and favors some groups over others. The only tax I am willing to support, ever, is some kind of single nationwide flat tax. Everyone pays the same percentage, and there are no rules, loopholes, tax breaks, or any of @#%$. You pay x percent and that's it. The full body of such a tax law should fit on a single index card... more than that and it's unnecessarily complex.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> While a balanced budget sounds good, it is not always possible. Some years you are going to have to run a defecit, and some years you will be in the black. Marketplace and world economic factors don't follow a fiscal year; things happen over the course of several years so it is silly to expect our government to respond by forcing our budget into an 'unnatural' budget. Let it reflect the economy. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
@#%$. Let them bank some money to cover hard times, just like we do. The system we have now is utterly ridiculous. The kind of amendment that would force them to keep it in the black is the simplest, best solution to their runaway budget problem.
<br />

<br />
You should also keep in mind that a libertarian government would lack something like 80% of the current government's size and complexity. No social security, no corporate bailouts, no public education, no war on drugs, no special funding for business interests... all of these things handed out to private companies, as it should be. The government in that situation requires a lot less money to run, and it becomes far easier for them to pay down the debt and keep their books in the black.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> In no way do I want to encourage more subsidies, however to a certain degree in some industries there are a real need of subsidies. For instance take a look at the human genome project. Much of it was subsidized by the NIH and other gvt agencies. NASA was a nice little government subsidies. I am convinced that we learned way more due to this 'crazy' subsidy than anything we lost. I would rather see our tax money used to subsidize certain things in various industries instead of seeing other countries subsidize those very same industries in their country. In some instances, such as the human genome project, the scientific knowledge of our country would fall far behind that of other countries. Many of you people argue for fuel cell powered vehicles, and if that is ever going to work it will require government subsidies. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
The government itself has no business giving subsidies. Let those in need of money turn to banks and other private entities to get it. That is the way a free market works. 
<br />

<br />
NASA is a good example of one that worked. Don't overlook, however, that Richard Branson (a private businessman) is going to outdo them within two decades. Also don't overlook how many projects fail. It is not a rosy success record.
<br />

<br />
Both ways work. Only one of them is permissible under our government's charter. I'd rather stick to the plan. If other countries outcompete us in medical technology (as India is doing now, for example), that's hardly the government's fault, nor is it their job to get us back on track.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Being that I used to work in the environmental testing field, I will atest to the fact that the government standards are not arbitrary. The LP then obviously does not understand this issue. If they do not understand this issue, then how can they develop a policy concerning this? I think we need a government agency to act as a third party. Else we will get a bunch of he said/she said stuff going on as companies or citizens accuse each other of pollution. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I think you are misinterpreting it. They are not saying the standards are arbitrary; they are saying arbitrary standards are not acceptable to them.
<br />

<br />
It seems pretty simple to me. Prove pollution, and take the sucker that did it to you off to the cleaners for it. That's what courts are for. Liability is one of the best ways to prevent someone from infringing on your rights.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> I am all for encouraging private schools, but I think it is crazy to totally eliminate government involvement in education. Universities, by the way, are another thing I think that should be subsidized by the federal government. As cliche as it sounds, eductation is indeed a major determining factor in the success of a society. I therefore feel that providing education to the citizens is one of the best things government can do. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I agree that there are, simply put, precious few things important than education to any successful society. This argument in favor of government education, however, has never made any sense to me whatsoever. Here's why.
<br />

<br />
The USA has the best universities in the entire world, and the largest number of them. People travel from all over the entire world to come here and study, because it is the best place to learn, and it is widely accepted everywhere in the world that this is the case. All responsibility, financial and otherwise, is placed directly on the student. This education system is private and run by businesses and individuals.
<br />

<br />
The USA has one of the worst public education systems in the 'first world', consistently placing us well behind the education systems of other countries at or near our level of development. We consistently turn out students who are unable to meet even the government's admittedly very low standards of competency. All responsibility is placed soley on the shoulders of the government. This education system is public and run by government.
<br />

<br />
There is only one major difference between these systems: private vs public. That's fucking all, ladies and gentlemen. Case closed.
<br />

<br />
I don't know exactly how you would go about changing the public education system into a private one; it's a very tough problem. It does, however, NEED to be done. The sooner we get started on it, the better off we will be.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Complete? As in remove the FDA? I think this is yet another misinformed and, for lack of a better term, stupid idea on part of the LP. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
