</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> The entire problem with the libertarian party is that while some of you are, you know, rational, and understand that limiting the government too far would be disastrous, there are far more of you that can't look at long-term effects at all. The ideas that you propose would generate mass chaos and a decline of the country in general, due to the simple fact that you're ignorant of how a country is run. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I hope you aren't implying that democrats or republicans (people, not elected officials) have a better idea than how the country is run than libertarians do. I'd think quite the opposite. Libertarians at least are aware of third party alternatives and the fuckery of the current election system, and that's more than most people.
<br />

<br />
I think if the LP ever did somehow come into power, their stances on a number of things (particularly, their ideas on how to abolish or phase large parts of government into private business) would compromise in a big damn hurry, precisely because they'd be getting a better idea how things work. Our current government certainly does its best to obscure all of that information every chance it gets. I can't imagine the anarcho-capitalist sect becoming the dominant philosophy in the party, ever. Of course, I didn't think the fascist segment of the republican party would be either, but lately that seems to be the trend.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
