<br />
Absolutely the case.  For example, I am NOT an open borders kind of person.  I think you take a severe risk of losing your country if you don't control the borders.
<br />

<br />
I also would not favor the elimination of OSHA.  One of the few proper roles of government is protection of rights, even working peoples right to life, lol.
<br />

<br />
And as a relatively new member of the Civil Service, and having experience with it in the past, I can state unequivically that, despite a paper trail veneer of being a merit system, it is a corrupt nest of cronyism, nepotism, and favoritism.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> sincerely doubt you can find more than ten universities in this country that do not receive some level of government funding</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
The universities, with very little exception, do NOT recieve the funding directly.  Individual students receive funding with which to pay education expenses.  This makes all the difference in the world, as an element of competition remains between schools.  To the extent, however, that the government has allowed price fixing, it has basically resulted in artificially inflated price increases for higher education.  It has been, and probably remains, common practice for schools to consult with each other over select students and tailor the packages they offer so that the net cost to the family is close to the same no matter which institution they attend.  That way, decisions are made on educational results rather than price, and price is steadily rising because the acutal customer doesn't end up paying it, the government does.  Clinton's higher education tax credit caused an immediate jump in higher education cost almost exactly equal to the credit, lol.
<br />

<br />
In any case, the principle remains sound.  Private education produces quality results.  Public education is crap.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">See whichever post it was in which I pointed out what happens when only the people who use a service fund it. 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
If they can't afford it, they shouldn't get it.  Pay your own way, buddy.<br />
