</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>EvilNight wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
Owning a gun is your right under the US Government, unlike driving a car. Personally I don't have a problem with requiring gun registration, basic training, or even a short waiting period... provided, in the end, that anyone who wants to buy a gun is allowed to do so.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I think it is reasonable to NOT allow people convicted of gun crimes in purchasing any future guns.  If somebody shows a precedent for using guns in a criminal behaviour, then they should not be allowed to buy it.
<br />
From the sound of it, your view on gun 'control' is contrary to the LP.  They do not want <span style="font-style: italic">any</span> regulation.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
We hardly have reasonable intervention. It is not the job of the government to bail out failing corporations. If they fail, that is simply the way the market works. I think you're overstating the libertarian view a bit here... their take is to go as hands-off as possible. The current government is hands-on in many ways that they simply do not need to be.
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
The government may seem "too big" in some people's eyes, but I really do not think it is all that bad as it is now.  We are hardly a dictatorship or communistic style government.  I think the US government has reasonable intervention for the most part.  Additionally the US government does not go bailling out failling corporations left and right.  Heck I can't even think of the last time (S&amp;L crises ~20 years ago?).  Even after 9/11, the single biggest attack on domestic soil, the US government refused to provide financial assistance to the airlines.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> 
<br />
There are plenty of other ways to get funding (tons of it, actually) than taxes. Personally I don't mind paying taxes, however, I do not like the current tax system, because it is corrupt and easily exploitable, and favors some groups over others. The only tax I am willing to support, ever, is some kind of single nationwide flat tax. Everyone pays the same percentage, and there are no rules, loopholes, tax breaks, or any of @#%$. You pay x percent and that's it. The full body of such a tax law should fit on a single index card... more than that and it's unnecessarily complex.
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Interesting that you mention there are several methods for the government to collect funds yet the only thing you can cite as evidence is yet another tax.
<br />
I think you are massively oversimplifying the tax system by wanting something to fit on an index card.  We have a very complex economy, and as such we need a complex tax system.
<br />
I think the LP mentions things like making a stuipidly simple tax system just for the PR spin, however it is craziness to think you can solve some complex issues with one simple flat percentage rate.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> 
<br />
@#%$. Let them bank some money to cover hard times, just like we do. The system we have now is utterly ridiculous. The kind of amendment that would force them to keep it in the black is the simplest, best solution to their runaway budget problem.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Government budgets do not work like a business budget.  Which is a good thing, actually.  You really don't want a government to save money for 'hard times.'  Who defines a hard time and where do you expect that money to be kept?  Oh, sure the government could put that in a savings account at a bank and that would open a can of worms in regards to favortism or government interferring with the market.  A government must estimate their costs and spend 100% of what they intend to; well that is it in a nutshell.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
The government itself has no business giving subsidies. Let those in need of money turn to banks and other private entities to get it. That is the way a free market works. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Which is fine and that is what happens in most cases.  However there are some ventures that are just too risky and it would be insane for some bank to put their %@$# on the line.  NASA, again, would be a great example.  Could you imagine some dude in 1963 going to Bank of America and getting a $300 million dollar loan on a hunch he could put a guy on the moon?
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
NASA is a good example of one that worked. Don't overlook, however, that Richard Branson (a private businessman) is going to outdo them within two decades. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
It is irrelevent because there is a time gap of 50 years.  Great private industry finally caught up to NASA circa 1960.  Those X-Prize people were not really breaking new ground, but rather just taking a different path.  What they are doing is not new; how they are doing it is.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
 If other countries outcompete us in medical technology (as India is doing now, for example), that's hardly the government's fault, nor is it their job to get us back on track.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I think it is the government's role to make sure we are as competitive as possible in the world.  The last thing I want are the Chinese (for example) zooming right ahead of us in space exploration.  They will probably laugh at our quaint government hand's off and totally free market system while the first man on Mars is a Chinese dude.
<br />
You may enjoy the notion of the government not getting involved at all in things, but I think that would be one of the worst things that could happen and would quickly bring about our downfall as a nation.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
I think you are misinterpreting it. They are not saying the standards are arbitrary; they are saying arbitrary standards are not acceptable to them.
<br />

<br />
It seems pretty simple to me. Prove pollution, and take the sucker that did it to you off to the cleaners for it. That's what courts are for. Liability is one of the best ways to prevent someone from infringing on your rights.
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Who, though, would be there to define what pulltion is?  You must be able to quantitate a value and state that over this level it is unacceptable and under this level is acceptable.  The government agencies are a great third party to set such regulations.  Let us look at something like smog, the liklihood that Joe Six Pack could succesfully sue MegaCorp for polluting his neighborhood is just about nil.  The ability for the federal government to step in and fine the hell out of MegaCorp is very likley.  Many times, contrary to what naysayers state, the federal government does fight the fight for the 'little guy.'
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
The USA has one of the worst public education systems in the 'first world', consistently placing us well behind the education systems of other countries at or near our level of development.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
This is one of those many little 'factoids' that has made it into society, but it is not quite true.  The US does rank below many of our peers, but there is a good reason.  When the US tests public students, all students are tested regardless if they are in special ed remedial class or advanced placement honors classes.  In most other countries, only the students in the academic tracks are tested, as opposed to students in the "lower" tradeskills class.  So basically what happens is that the US testing data includes those scores from students dumber than a doorknob yet testing data from other countries (e.g. Japan) only includes those students who will attend university.  Hardly a fair comparison.  The US is one of the few countries that all students are given an equal chance.  In so many countries across the world if a kid fucks up on a test when he is 13, he could be screwed for life.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Have these people ever have a job? Working in the chemistry field I am hella happy for OSHA. OSHA has, without a doubt in my mind, saved many many lifes. I fail to see how OSHA regulations are something that we need to eliminate. Again, working in the chemistry field, i.e. hazardous materials, I am thankful as hell for OSHA. It is nice to know that companies are required to send a Material Safety Data Sheet (MSDS) with their product so I know what the hell it is! </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Dunno much about OSHA either. Care to link some relevant literature?</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Guess you can go <a href="http://www.osha.gov/" target="_blank" class="postlink">HERE</a>.  Essentially OSHA protects the rights of workers, as somebody else touched on.  OSHA makes sure my employer provides safety devices.  I suppose in the Libertarian world without OSHA my family could sue my employer for my untimely death and win some $$ but frankly I wouldn't care because I would be dead.  OSHA covers anything from requiring employers to provide work boots that meet minimal safety standards to things like making sure the air is breathable in the work place.
<br />
In a way OSHA is like a watchdog for the employees of the nation.  OSHA, arguably, is one of the few branches of government that I am 100% happy with and believe that they function quite well.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
Not at all. Go ahead and name any military actions we took in recent years that were in response to a treaty violation, or an attack on our sovereign nation. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
The 1991 Gulf War was in response to UN violations, which is a treaty that the US is indeed part of.  The actions in Kosovo and Bosnia were based on our treaty with NATO.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">It's clear we're doing a lot more internationally than what we are constitutionally supposed to be doing. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
While you argue that the Constitution does not allow the US to stick our nose in world events, it does not deny it either.  The constitution gives the President powers to negotiate with other countries and the Constitution empowers the government with a military force.  I firmly believe that the founding fathers put two and two together and realize that one day our government would go around the world 'handling business.'
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Frankly, I'd rather we reigned that in for awhile and fixed the problems we have at home. It's not our job to prop up the rest of the civilized world every time they get a skinned knee or bloody nose. Tsunami relief is a good example of the kind of aid I would approve of, but not much else. At least not until we get our own house in order.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
We will never, ever until the end of time ever get all of our domestic problems 100% solved.
<br />
Never.
<br />
There will always be something amiss.  Therefore it is futile, and quite ignorant in my opinion, to think that we should not involve ourself in world politics while we have domestic issues.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
