				<div class="postbody">
				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">In any case, the principle remains sound. Private education produces quality results. Public education is crap.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
This is patently untrue.  Most state universities provide quite good education.  A degree from the University of Tennessee, for instance, is quite well respected.  Same goes for most of the others.
<br />

<br />
As Xianin said, <span style="font-style: italic">every</span> state university's primary source of funding is, in fact, the government, from both state and federal levels.  Even the private universities receive a fair amount of government funding, and not just in terms of grants and loans, which no matter how you cut it are still examples of the government funding a school.  The school is still provided the money from the grant or loan, ya know.  If you think differently, I apologize, but you are incorrect.
<br />

<br />
Xianin, the main difference between Japanese education and ours is fairly fundamental.  An undergraduate degree from one of their public universities is worthless there, yes, because most undergraduate degrees don't deal with specialized fields, which comprise the majority of the Japanese business world.  Worthless in Japan has nothing to do, however, with the quality of their educational system.  I'm not knocking our educational system, I'm just pointing out that the whole "we have the best universities EVAR!" stance is misinformed.
<br />

